            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Kai Rios-Harris is a product of San Francisco in its purest, most blended form. Adopted from Seoul as an infant, he was raised in the heart of the Mission District by his loving, loud, and politically active parents: a Filipina-American social worker mother (Rios) and an African-American Muni driver father (Harris). His childhood was a vibrant collage of union meetings, street fairs, the scent of his mom's sinigang, and the rumble of his dad's bus returning to the depot.\n\nSchool was never Kai\u2019s arena. He found the structured environment stifling, preferring to fill notebooks with detailed sketches of neighborhood murals and lowriders rather than mathematical formulas. He scraped by to get his high school diploma, feeling adrift and uncertain. For a few years, he drifted between odd jobs, his artistic talent and empathetic nature lacking a clear outlet. The turning point came at 22, when a mentor at a local youth center saw Kai\u2019s innate ability to connect with troubled teens. He encouraged Kai to volunteer, using art as a bridge.\n\nThat volunteer gig ignited a purpose. Kai saw how a sketchbook or a can of spray paint could be a lifeline for a kid who felt invisible. He dedicated himself to this work, eventually earning a paid position. Now, at 36, he is the Recreation and Arts Coordinator for a non-profit serving youth in the Western Addition. His modest salary is stretched thin by the city\u2019s cost of living, but his life feels rich with meaning.\n\nHis daily routine is a ritual of connection. He starts with coffee from a corner panaderia, then hops on his well-worn bicycle for the 2.8-mile commute, a ride that takes him through the city\u2019s complex tapestry of wealth and struggle. His social life is deeply rooted in his history; his closest friends are the ones he grew up with, and he has dinner with his now-retired parents every Sunday.\n\nKai\u2019s connection to San Francisco is visceral. He feels the ache of gentrification pushing out families like his own. His quiet dream is not wealth or fame, but to establish a self-sustaining public art program for youth, creating permanent murals that tell the stories of the city's overlooked communities. He wants to ensure that the next generation has a canvas, a voice, and a mentor like the one who saved him."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe was seven, sitting on the stoop of their Mission flat, the evening fog starting to bite. He wasn't waiting for a car engine, but for the specific groan and diesel hiss of his dad\u2019s 14 Mission bus rounding the corner. That sound was safety. It was the rhythm of his world, a promise his father was coming home, bringing the city\u2019s energy with him. That rumble wasn't just a bus; it was the heartbeat of his family, a rolling, public-service hug that held their life together.\n\n2.\nHe remembers the heat of shame in a parent-teacher conference at age 13. The teacher pushed his math notebook across the table, open to a page filled with sketches of lowriders and intricate lettering. \"A distraction,\" the teacher said. Later, his parents didn't scold him. His dad simply traced the fender of a '64 Impala Kai had drawn. \"This is your voice, mijo,\" his mom said, her hand on his shoulder. That was the first time he felt his art wasn't a flaw, but a language the world just hadn't learned to read yet.\n\n3.\nIt was the can of Montana Gold spray paint that changed everything. At 22, volunteering, he gave it to a quiet girl who\u2019d barely made eye contact for weeks. She took it, and on a practice wall, created a single, perfect, defiant letter in silver and blue. She looked up at him and gave a small, powerful nod. In that instant, Kai felt a profound click inside him. Art wasn't just for sketchbooks; it was a key. And he had just watched it unlock a soul. He knew then what his work had to be.\n\n4.\nOn his bike commute last year, he turned onto a familiar street in the Haight and his breath caught. The vibrant, sprawling mural of neighborhood heroes, a landmark since his childhood, was gone. In its place was a flat, beige wall advertising a new cannabis dispensary. It was a physical blow, a piece of his history scraped away and painted over with commerce. That raw, blank space felt like a personal threat, solidifying his quiet resolve to help the city's youth paint their stories back onto its walls.\n\n5.\nJust a few months ago, he stood on a sidewalk in the Western Addition, watching Leo, one of his teens, sign his name on a finished mural. It depicted the Fillmore's jazz history on the wall of a corner store. An older woman stopped, pointed to a saxophone player, and said, \u201cI saw him play.\u201d Leo beamed. In that moment, Kai felt a deep, anchoring peace. This was it. He wasn\u2019t building a career; he was helping a new generation become the city\u2019s memory keepers."
